DistantHorizons.config.client.graphics.q:
The maximum detail fake chunks are rendered at.

§6Fastest:§r Chunk
§6Fanciest:§r Block
The mod's render distance, measured in chunks.

How well fake chunks represent overhangs, caves, cliffsides, etc.

Higher options will increase memory and GPU usage.

How quickly fake chunks drop off in quality.

Larger numbers will improve how distant terrain looks
but will increase memory and GPU usage.

How far apart drops in quality are.

Higher settings will increase the distance between drops
but will increase memory and GPU usage.

How detail dropoff is calculated.

Higher settings will make the drop-off less noticeable
but will increase how often the geometry has to be rebuilt,
increasing CPU usage and the chance of stuttering.

This is the same as vanilla Biome Blending settings for Lod area. 

Note that anything other than '0' will greatly effect Lod building time
and increase triangle count. The cost on chunk generation speed is also 
quite large if set to too high.

'0' equals to Vanilla Biome Blending of '1x1', 
'1' equals to Vanilla Biome Blending of '3x3', 
'2' equals to Vanilla Biome Blending of '5x5'...
DistantHorizons.config.client.graphics.f: The distance(s) Fog will be rendered on fake chunks.
When fog will be rendered on fake chunks.
The color of the fog on fake chunks.

§6True:§r disables Minecraft's fog on vanilla chunks.
§6False:§r Minecraft renders fog like normal.

May cause issues with other mods that edit fog.
Disable if vanilla chunks are completely covered in fog.

Where should the far fog start? 

  '0.0': Fog start at player's position.
  '1.0': The fog-start's circle fit just in the lod render distance square.
'1.414': The lod render distance square fit just in the fog-start's circle.

Where should the far fog end? 

  '0.0': Fog end at player's position.
  '1.0': The fog-end's circle fit just in the lod render distance square.
'1.414': The lod render distance square fit just in the fog-end's circle.

What is the minimum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

What is the maximum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

How the fog thickness should be calculated from distance?

LINEAR: Linear based on distance (will ignore 'density')
EXPONENTIAL: 1/(e^(distance*density)) 
EXPONENTIAL_SQUARED: 1/(e^((distance*density)^2)

How the height should effect the fog thickness combined with the normal function? 

BASIC: No special height fog effect. Fog is calculated based on camera distance 
IGNORE_HEIGHT: Ignore height completely. Fog is calculated based on horizontal distance 
ADDITION: heightFog + farFog 
MAX: max(heightFog, farFog) 
MULTIPLY: heightFog * farFog 
INVERSE_MULTIPLY: 1 - (1-heightFog) * (1-farFog) 
LIMITED_ADDITION: farFog + max(farFog, heightFog) 
MULTIPLY_ADDITION: farFog + farFog * heightFog 
INVERSE_MULTIPLY_ADDITION: farFog + 1 - (1-heightFog) * (1-farFog) 
AVERAGE: farFog*0.5 + heightFog*0.5 

Note that for 'BASIC' mode and 'IGNORE_HEIGHT' mode, fog settings for height fog has no effect.

Where should the height fog be located? 

ABOVE_CAMERA: Height fog starts from camera to the sky 
BELOW_CAMERA: Height fog starts from camera to the void 
ABOVE_AND_BELOW_CAMERA: Height fog starts from camera to both the sky and the void 
ABOVE_SET_HEIGHT: Height fog starts from a set height to the sky 
BELOW_SET_HEIGHT: Height fog starts from a set height to the void 
ABOVE_AND_BELOW_SET_HEIGHT: Height fog starts from a set height to both the sky and the void
If the height fog is calculated around a set height, what is that height position?

How far the start of height fog should offset? 

  '0.0': Fog start with no offset.
  '1.0': Fog start with offset of the entire world's height. (Include depth)

How far the end of height fog should offset? 

  '0.0': Fog end with no offset.
  '1.0': Fog end with offset of the entire world's height. (Include depth)

What is the minimum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

What is the maximum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

How the fog thickness should be calculated from height? 

LINEAR: Linear based on height (will ignore 'density')
EXPONENTIAL: 1/(e^(height*density)) 
EXPONENTIAL_SQUARED: 1/(e^((height*density)^2)
DistantHorizons.config.client.graphics.a:
How should the LODs be rendered?
NOTE: Currently only CUBIC is implemented!

§6False:§r fake chunks behind the player's camera aren't rendered, improving performance.
§6True:§r fake chunks are always rendered.

Leave False unless you see fake chunks disappearing at the edge of your vision.

§6False:§r fake chunks will drop off in quality the farther from the player they are, improving performance.
§6True:§r all fake chunks will be rendered at the highest available detail level.

Enabling this will drastically increase memory and GPU usage.

Determines how often fake chunks will be rendered on top of regular chunks.

§6Dynamic:§r attempts to pick the best option based on vanilla render distance and dimension.
§6Always:§r prevents holes in the world, but may look odd for transparent blocks or in caves.
§6Border:§r renders fake chunks on the border of the vanilla render distance, preventing gaps when the player isn't moving.
§6Never:§r fake chunks will never overlap the vanilla render distance, but there may be holes in the world.

If on Vanilla Overdraw mode of NEVER, how much should should the border be offset? 

 '1': The start of lods will be shifted inwards by 1 chunk, causing 1 chunk of overdraw. 
'-1': The start fo lods will be shifted outwards by 1 chunk, causing 1 chunk of gap. 

This setting can be used to deal with gaps due to our vanilla rendered chunk 
  detection not being perfect.

Will prevent some overdraw issues,
but may cause nearby fake chunks to render incorrectly, especially when near fancy leaves.
Less noticeable with a longer vanilla render distance.
The distance where the back side of fake chunks aren't rendered to improve performance.

How bright fake chunk colors are.

0 = black 
1 = normal 
2 = near white

How saturated fake chunk colors are.

0 = black and white 
1 = normal 
2 = vibrant

If enabled caves will be culled 

§6NOTE§r: This feature is under development and 
 it is VERY experimental! Please don't report 
any issues related to this feature. 

Additional Info: Currently this cull all faces 
 with skylight value of 0 in dimensions that 
 does not have a ceiling.

any issues related to this feature.
DistantHorizons.config.client.worldGener: The priority for chunks being generated around the player.

How complicated the generation should be when generating fake chunks outside the vanilla render distance.

§6§6Fastest:§r Biome only
§6Best Quality:§r Features (suggested)
§6Best compatability:§r Full (Very slow, don't use unless the fake chunks generate incorrectly.)

Some features may not be thread safe.
Could cause instability and crashes
Defines the types of blocks to ignore when generating fake chunks.

§6True:§r in single player fake chunks will be generated outside the vanilla render distance.
Note: this can use a large amount of CPU.

§6False:§r fake chunks will only generate within the vanilla render distance.

§6Fancy:§r use Minecraft's lighting engine, gives accurate lighting.
§6Fast:§r estimate block lighting, shadows won't be as smooth.

If the fake chunks appear black, set this to §6Fast:§r.
DistantHorizons.config.client.multiplaye:
Determines the folder format for local multiplayer data.

§6Auto:§r
Uses "Name, IP" for LAN worlds and "Name, IP, Port" for standard multiplayer.
§6Name Only:§r
Uses the server browser name. Ex: "Minecraft Server"
§6Name IP:§r
"Minecraft Server, IP 192.168.1.40"
§6Name, IP, Port:§r
"Minecraft Server, IP 192.168.1.40:25565"
§6Name, IP, Port, MC Version:§r
"Minecraft Server, IP 192.168.1.40:25565, GameVersion 1.18.1"

§c§lCaution:§r changing while connected to a multiplayer server may cause glitches.

When matching worlds of the same dimension type the
tested chunks must be at least this percent the same
in order to be considered the same world.

Note: If you use portals to enter a dimension at two
different locations this system may think it is two different worlds.

§61.0:§r the chunks must be identical.
§60.5:§r the chunks must be half the same.
§60.0:§r disables multi-dimension support
     only one world will be used per dimension.
DistantHorizons.config.client.advanced.t:
The number of threads used to generate fake chunks
outside the normal render distance.
If you experience stuttering when generating fake chunks: decrease this number.
If you want to increase LOD generation speed: increase this number.

Can only be between 1 and your CPU's processor count.

The number of threads used when building vertex buffers
(The things sent to your GPU to draw the fake chunks).
Can only be between 1 and your CPU's processor count.
DistantHorizons.config.client.advanced.b:
The method for uploading geometry to the GPU.

If you experience stuttering while your CPU and GPU usage is low, try changing this setting.
Note: if you are in a world you may have to leaving and rejoin to see the full effect.

How long should a buffer wait per Megabyte of data uploaded?
May be increased if there is frame stuttering.
How frequently should vertex buffers (geometry) be rebuilt and sent to the GPU?
